‚ÄúThis program is important::: because while art-marking is flourishing in many Native communities‚Äîespecially along the Northwest Coast‚Äîin other communities there are few teachers and even fewer historical artworks from which to learn:::‚Äù Dr. Kathryn Bunn-Marcuse::: director of the Bill Holm Center and Burke Museum curator of Northwest Native art said.

Grant applications for 2022 are open until December 3::: 2021. Native and First Nations artists can apply at burkemuseum.org/bhcgrants. The grants are made possible thanks to funding by the Henry Luce Foundation.

A car accident changed how Ather Sharif thought about accessibility. Now::: he's changing others' minds too.

‚ÄúIt was only after I became a part of the disability community that I started to realize how inequitable the world is for people with disabilities::: and I wanted to do something to fix that using the skills I already had:::‚Äù Sharif said.

As a doctoral student in the Paul G. Allen School of Computer Science & Engineering at UW::: Sharif believes in the idea of personalized design::: that technology should be built to adapt to the needs of a user. This is different from universal design::: which::: while commonly touted as being designed for everyone::: Sharif argues it is designed for the majority::: and people who aren‚Äôt in the majority must adapt to use it. Sharif is studying accessibility in technology::: especially in visualizations::: and how they can be better designed for people who are blind or have low vision.

#HuskyExperience University of Washington Graduate School

Read more: https://www.grad.uw.edu/ather-sharif/

Sam Dubal was in a hurry to change the world. Determined to address inequities in medicine::: he earned a medical degree and a PhD in medical anthropology by the time he was 31. One month into his new position::: Dubal ‚Äî an avid hiker ‚Äî disappeared on Mt. Rainier. His life and stellar career were cut short.

"They also don‚Äôt fully mature into adult cells. But we‚Äôre hoping that by exposing them to other chemical signals they‚Äôll mature even further.‚Äù

column3:
Thanks for sharing. I really appreciate it.
For me::: another source of mental health comes from discrimination.
Below are a few stories.

In May 2016::: my advisor::: also a faculty member in charge of ME 520 (Graduate seminar)::: attempted to maintain discipline after some graduate students disturbed the invited speaker from another university. The group of students::: claiming that they presented the whole ME department as MEGA (mechanical engineering graduate association::: me_chat@uw.edu)
and the Mechanical Engineering department chair supported them::: sent massive emails to slender my advisor. Only 70 students attended ME 520::: but the massive emails reached out to 700 current and past students. To the best of my knowledge::: abusing unnecessarily many emails without official purpose and consent is illegal. I believe that my advisor has been in a mental breakdown. He left UW in 2020.

It is hard for international students to be selected to TA and instructors. The ME department has been in favor of a few beloved graduate students. For example::: three graduate students have been assigned instructors for as many as eight quarters. Can you imagine a senior-level course offered in 2016 taught by a graduate student who got an undergraduate degree in 2015? Can you imagine a graduate student being assigned as the TA of one course because they just failed in the same course last quarter? It is a joke that the department declares that it values diversity::: equality::: and inclusion. At the same time::: international students like me have been imposed a lot of requirements. The department has been treating students with double standards. That hurts a lot of international students mentally.

When I raised the issue to the department and its graduate student association::: I was yelled at by the post-doc of the department chair that I had made no positive contribution to the department so that my words were useless. I was also accused of reporting unfair TA assignments.

During the academic year 16/17::: I have reported to several units beyond the ME department::: including Vice Provost Dr. Taylor. But I had never received any response. Instead::: a few weeks later::: my advisor told me that he had been annoyed and pressured by the department to request me to keep my mouth shut and delete my thoughts on my own Facebook page.

I felt hopeless and have thought of committing suicide. I did not want to see my advisor bullied because of me. Fortunately::: I did not. If I died::: the ME department would celebrate.

(The associate dean at the college level has talked with me and he seemed willing to let me share my thoughts. But it seems that he can not do anything as all these things are too old to handle. I fully understand)

I hope my voice will not be filtered. Everyone::: regardless of race::: is equal. Black Lives Matter. Stop Asian Hate.

This #TBT we return to some essential moments in Seattle for #LGBTHistoryMonth history. In 1933::: same-sex bars like The Double Header::: began to open to combat Washington‚Äôs sodomy laws. The Double Header is said to be the longest-operating gay bar in the nation until it closed in 2015. Gay bars in the 1930s were prominent in the Pioneer Square area and helped working-class men and women look for partners.

Drag performances became a crucial feature of the LGBTQIA+ community. Among them is drag artist Francis Renault (pictured here in the second photo)::: known for embodying actress Lillian Russell.

The first Gay Pride March::: captured here in the third photo::: was in 1977. What started as Gay Pride week initiated the annual celebration of LGBTQIA+ Pride and began Capitol Hill‚Äôs reputation as the center for increasing visibility of sexual minorities. In the 1990s::: many LGBTQIA+ organizations emerged to address minorities of distinct racial and cultural backgrounds::: such as Emerald City Black Pride::: Pride Asia::: Entre Hermanos::: Trikone Northwest::: Noor and many more.

Seattle‚Äôs LGBTQIA+ history has been about laws::: morality::: understanding::: cultural and political expressions and city space. It is imperative to recognize Seattle community members who have challenged heterosexist oppression and fought to live a life free of judgment and persecution.

Struggling with social anxiety? Right as Rain by UW Medicine has five tips to help. One way? Normalize and name the anxiety.

‚ÄúI‚Äôm struck with how hard it is to say to someone you are with that you are feeling socially anxious::: but it doesn‚Äôt hurt to disclose that. Chances are::: the other person is feeling that too:::‚Äù says Lori Zoellner::: a psychology professor at the University of Washington.

‚ÄúPlant fossil remains from this time period are crucial for our understanding of the wider ecosystem. Not only can plant material tell us what these dinosaurs were perhaps eating::: but plants can more broadly tell us what their environment looked like:::‚Äù UW Earth and Space Sciences and Burke Museum Graduate Student Paige Wilson said. ‚ÄúPlants are the base of the food chain and a crucial part of the fossil record. A shortage of ventilators became a worldwide crisis in March 2020 with the arrival of COVID. Within weeks::: a volunteer team of clinicians and engineers ‚Äî many from the UW ‚Äî committed to developing a low-cost ventilator that could be stockpiled for use in intensive care units but also used in settings with limited resources.

The result is WorldVent::: a streamlined ventilator that can be rapidly and easily produced. WorldVent performs the same life-saving function as highly-technical ICU ventilators at a fraction of the cost.

column1: Looking for a nearby park to check out with your roommate? Gas Works is an option! Fun fact: Gas Works Park was developed as a gas works plant in 1906 by the Seattle Light Company. Dr. Thomas Grabowski::: who directs the UW Medicine Alzheimer Disease Research Center::: discusses the latest Alzheimer's advances and research in progress.

One of the biggest questions: Will we have a cure in our lifetime?

"On June 7::: 2021::: we entered a new era in Alzheimer‚Äôs research upon the FDA‚Äôs approval of aducanumab for patients diagnosed with Alzheimer‚Äôs:::" says Grabowski. "We are where HIV/AIDS was 20 years ago when AZT came along as the first medication to stop the progression of a disease with no treatment or cure. Over time::: more and more medications came on the market::: which were less toxic::: more effective::: and now people with HIV/AIDS are living normal lives. We think Alzheimer‚Äôs will be like that. We will be able to improve on this first step with aducanumab."

#WorldAlzheimersDay

Meet Casey! The Center for Conservation Biology uses dogs for scat detection work. With a nose for whale scat::: Casey helps track the health of the southern resident killer whale population. üê≥ üí©

In 1997::: Dr. Samuel Wasser::: the founder of Conservation Canines and a research professor in the UW Department of Biology::: had his ‚Äúeureka‚Äù moment ‚Äî at a conference where dog handlers described their scent-training techniques. Dr. Wasser began to modify detection dog methods to train canines to locate scat from endangered species. Since then::: Conservation Canines has been monitoring various threatened species such as orcas::: tigers::: wolves::: bears and spotted owls.

The ideal detection dog is highly focused with such high energy that they are often turned away by their original owners. They are happy to work all day successfully locating wildlife scat. Conservation Canines offers these dogs the opportunity to help save numerous other species ‚Äî and gain a new lease on life themselves.

Read more here: https://bit.ly/ConservationK9

SHAME ON UW. New UW Primate Center Director Was Once Suspended for Violations. It‚Äôs both appalling and disturbingly telling that the University of Washington (UW) would hire Michele Basso to lead the troubled Washington National Primate Research Center (WaNPRC)::: which has been without a director for nearly 18 months. Basso is notorious for being one of the few university experimenters ever to be suspended from using animals as a result of serious welfare violations.

Her time at the University of Wisconsin was marked by a firestorm over the number of monkeys in her studies who died::: her unwillingness to abide by regulations or adhere to experimental protocols::: and her apparent incompetence. As the University of Wisconsin chancellor wrote in a memo sent to all faculty on March 19::: 2010::: ‚ÄúDr. Michele Basso ‚Ä¶ has been cited by university animal care committees for a range of problems over a five-and-a-half
-year period. Despite repeated efforts and an unambiguous warning by the School of Medicine and Public Health‚Äôs ‚Ä¶ ACUC [Animal Care and Use Committee]::: problems recurred.‚Äù The Michele Basso Appointment Spells More Suffering for Monkeys in UW Laboratories. CLOSE UW PRIMATE CENTER In 2013::: Harvard University closed its primate center after looking critically at its multiple animal welfare violations::: the difficulty of keeping monkeys in laboratories::: and the future of its research priorities. It‚Äôs time that the University of Washington followed suit.

The federally funded Washington National Primate Research Center (WaNPRC) at the University of Washington (UW) rakes in tens of millions of tax dollars but hasn‚Äôt been able to abide by even the most basic animal protection laws. Monkeys have died from strangulation::: starvation::: dehydration::: veterinary error::: and choking on their own vomit. Internal documents reveal that in one recent eight-month period::: the primate center had to treat a staggering 332 traumatic injuries (such as broken limbs and teeth)::: more than 200 cases of gastrointestina
l problems::: 149 cases of significant weight loss::: 19 cases of rectal prolapse::: and a dozen implant abnormalities.

Monkeys are sentient beings who experience pain::: suffering::: joy::: and fear::: just as humans do. In nature::: they live in large family groups::: forming strong bonds with one another. They play::: eat::: explore::: and socialize together. They‚Äôre also empathic::: often risking their own lives to help others. They need to be protected::: not experimented on.

WASHINGTON.EDU
UW::: Carnegie Mellon to pioneer platforms that harness astrophysical data to unravel the universe‚Äôs mysteries

University of Washington College of Arts & Sciences
3 September::: 08:09 ¬∑

Close your eyes and imagine the night sky filled with billions of stars::: galaxies::: stellar clusters and asteroids. Incredible::: right? Over the next decade::: those celestial images will be captured through the Legacy Survey of Space and Time (LSST) at the Rubin Observatory in Chile.

The University of Washington is one of the four founders of the LSST Project::: which will be the most ambitious and comprehensive optical astronomy survey ever undertaken. And faculty and researchers from UW‚Äôs Data Intensive Research in Astrophysics and Cosmology Institute (DiRAC) will play leading roles in developing its science capabilities and data processing pipelines.

The LSST camera will capture 20 terabytes of data each night. And in order to make discoveries from such large datasets::: DiRAC and Carnegie Mellon University will collaborate on developing new software platforms to help astronomers make sense of the output.

These open-source platforms are part of the new LSST Interdisciplinary Network for Collaboration and Computing (LINCC)::: and will ultimately create a fundamental change in how scientists use modern computational methods to make sense of big data.

The LINCC analysis frameworks are supported by Schmidt Futures::: a philanthropic initiative founded by Eric and Wendy Schmidt. This project is part of Schmidt Futures‚Äô work in astrophysics::: which aims to accelerate our knowledge about the universe by supporting the development of software and hardware platforms to facilitate research across the field of astronomy.

"We're excited to build the toolkits for the next decade of data-driven astronomy:::‚Äù says Mario Juric::: the director of DiRAC. "These will unlock the full potential of LSST::: not just to DiRAC researchers::: but the astronomical community at large.‚Äù

Human vision is a sense that‚Äôs deeply complex. The way our bodies see and interact with the world is layered::: nuanced and difficult to mimic in machines.

However::: University of Washington Mechanical Engineering Assistant Professor Xu Chen believes that improving the integration of machine vision::: intelligence and manipulation is the key to making robotic systems that are better at assisting humans with complex tasks.

To advance robot vision::: Chen and his students in the UW Mechatronics::: Automation and Control Systems Lab have developed a variety of experimental systems. Some are practical::: while others are more fun ‚Äî like finishing a Rubik's Cube or playing chess.

‚ÄúWashington kind of separated itself::: one::: because of (former head coach) Tyrone Willingham:::‚Äù Walker said. ‚ÄúI trusted him. I really liked the guy. I knew he valued me not just as a football player but as a human being. He helped me grow into a man. I talked to him about how I wanted to do pre-med and it would require me to take some courses that would interfere with football a little bit. Obviously I‚Äôm going to give it my all to do football and school as much as possible::: but (becoming a doctor) is my No. 1 goal."

Not only was Walker a huge part of turning Washington's football program around::: but he also went on to become a surgeon ‚Äî just like his dad.

DJ's works include SoundWatch::: an app that provides always-available sound feedback on smartwatches. When the app picks up a nearby sound like a car honking::: a bird chirping or someone hammering::: it sends the user a notification along with information about the sound. ‚åö

#PhilanthropyFriday

‚ÄúMaking the world a better place‚Äù??? Lol. Sure. Like demanding folks come back to in person courses when it isn‚Äôt safe for them to do so. Students have to go through the disabilities office but that office has no idea what would lead to accommodations for COVID since so many underlying conditions that put folks at risk for severe illness‚Äîand having children too young to be vaccinated at home‚Äîaren‚Äôt considered disabilities. Oh UW::: your ableism really is showing.

High transmission. Full hospitals. A variant with R0 that‚Äôs close to 8‚Ä¶maybe higher. More breakthrough cases daily. Children 22% of all new cases. No actual plan for keeping students::: staff::: and faculty safe. Seems wise. But yeah::: please frame this as folks just being scared of other humans after being isolated rather than people being concerned for the well-being of our community while UW remains committed to watching the dollar.
column4:
I notice that there is a "Don't come to school if you're sick" and "If you catch it quarantine for 10 days" policy in place. That being said::: not a single staff member has addressed a plan of action as to how those students who fall ill are expected to make up classes or attend lectures. Missing two weeks in a 10 week quarter is a substantial amount of time to be absent and without solid alternatives::: I worry that it only incentivizes sick students to come to class sick.

I don't feel as if this is a matter of "if" students have to quarantine::: but when. How is the UW addressing this factor into operations this year? It's a lot of money on the line for those who are expecting in person classes but may be forced back into a virtual classroom and those who will wind up sick and failing classes at no fault of their own::: simply because no other alternative exists. Why is there not a hybrid option for all students? Or at the very least::: have course materials::: lecture recordings available online?

An advocate for equitable representation in science::: Nick Maurice was recently awarded the 2021 Graduate School Medal.

Maurice is a doctoral student in the Molecular and Cellular Biology program at the UW::: where he‚Äôs spent the past six years studying the complex language of cells in the immune system.

But he‚Äôs learned that just as important in learning the language of immunity is communicating that knowledge with the community. That‚Äôs why he participates in outreach programs in local high schools::: mentors young scientists and builds trust in science among groups that have historically been excluded from or marginalized by biomedical research.

"I have observed both through research and volunteer work::: that community mistrust in research further perpetuates a cycle of disproportionate burdens and skepticism. Representation is critical in addressing these fears:::" said Maurice.

#UWserves

University of Washington Civil & Environmental Engineering researchers studying shallow lakes in the Puget Sound region found they had proportionately more arsenic in the sediments near the shore than deeper lakes. This is due to unique characteristics that facilitate the movement of arsenic from lakebed sediment up into the surface waters and near-shore areas where the aquatic food web resides.

The researchers are in the early stages of working with the Washington State Department of Health to explore issuing a fish consumption advisory for the lakes. They also hope to create a screening tool to quickly determine if lakes have concerning levels of arsenic in the food web::: explore remediation technologies to remove arsenic from lakebeds::: and investigate the impact of arsenic on aquatic organisms.
#PopulationHealth #UWserves

According to documents obtained by PETA::: frequent escapes by monkeys imprisoned there are a common problem and aren‚Äôt always reported to authorities. I need not remind you that escapes are a blatant violation of the federal Animal Welfare Act and deserve immediate corrective action::: which does not appear to be forthcoming.

These escapes are the latest in what seem to be an endless stream of shocking revelations coming from the WaNPRC::: but what is more disturbing is that there seems to be no punitive action being taken to prevent escapes or violations. For instance::: the latest escape involved a monkey who went missing for two days before staff located her. In response to this escape::: authorities from the Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee ‚Äîwhich is charged with ensuring that all animal protection laws are enforced in the school‚Äôs laboratories‚Äîdi
d nothing at all.

In 2013::: Harvard University closed its primate center after looking critically at its multiple animal welfare violations::: the difficulty of keeping monkeys in laboratories::: and the future of its research priorities. It‚Äôs time that the University of Washington followed suit.

The interdisciplinary research team::: led by UW chemical engineering associate professor James Carothers::: has an initial goal to develop a cell-free system to convert CO2 into malic acid. Malic acid can be made into a variety of chemicals::: including maleic anhydride which had a 2018 market size of $2.77 billion and is used to make everything from plastics for cars and boats::: to water treatment detergents::: insecticides and fungicides and pharmaceuticals. Malic acid ‚Äî like most commodity chemicals ‚Äî is made using fossil fuels::: generating significant CO2 emissions in the process.

Hip hop's incredibly rich history & DNA can be found in just about every form of music. From African drumming to jazz::: funk & the blues::: UW students have been able to explore the annals of the genre through the University of Washington College of Arts & Sciences' course "Roots and Routes of Rap".

UW School of Music professor Christina Sunardi created the course with support from the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation through its Arts and Creativity Initiative. The initiative aims to spark creativity in students::: particularly those who may not be majoring in the arts.

After exploring rap‚Äôs musical influences::: the course dives into rap music itself::: with Seattle rap artist Asun (Suntonio Bandanaz) and DJ Neebor (Robin Neebor Clemente)::: a local DJ::: each visiting the class. In addition to weekly assignments::: students have begun working on a final project: writing a rap song::: which they will present to the class at the end of the quarter.

University of Washington Tacoma student Ashley Young::: Air Force veteran and women‚Äôs pro tackle football player::: responded quickly when she saw a fire break out in a Tacoma neighborhood on the 4th of July::: getting bystanders to dial 911 while she ran door to door to alert those near the fire.

When asked about her actions::: Young said::: halfway joking::: that "Women's pro tackle football helped with the running." The sport keeps her at peak conditioning::: practicing at elevation::: in hundred-plus-degree heat in Salt Lake City. As to the bravery reflex::: "Well::: that was all military." She modestly adds::: "I surprised myself. No time to think. Plus::: Dad taught me at an early age to always be prepared. You never know when you might find yourself in a serious situation where seconds count. I will continue to help our community whenever I can::: service-before-self is a part of being a service member that never leaves you.‚Äù

Over the years microplastics have become a subject we‚Äôre all familiar with::: but often overlooked and discussed with less urgency is microtrash. Trash left behind on beaches::: at parks and on trails break down over time into small pieces ‚Äî or microtrash.

So::: what can we do? The UW College of the Environment has some tips.

Having a critical eye for trash around you and picking up your own trash is crucial to healthy waterways::: uncontaminated oceans and the health of vulnerable species like orcas::: salmon and shellfish. Packing a trash bag when you picnic and collecting trash other may have left behind and participating in a trash clean up are just a couple of great ways to help!

From the start::: Seattle artist George Rodriguez::: '09::: explored identity::: culture and community in his work.

His pieces are clever::: playful and profound. Part of his style centers on ornamentation and detail. He hand forms tiny leaves and rosettes and elements to adorn the larger figures he‚Äôs creating.

In 2006::: he enrolled in the UW‚Äôs MFA program where Akio Takamori::: one of his heroes::: was teaching. Rodriguez wanted to study with somebody working in figurative sculptures::: and that was Takamori‚Äôs metier. ‚ÄúAnd the UW had one of the top programs in the country for clay:::‚Äù says Rodriguez::: ‚Äô09. When the budding artist came to scout the school::: Takamori introduced him to the clay community. Rodriguez was dazzled. ‚ÄúIt was like your hero taking you to see the town:::‚Äù he says.

Today::: Rodriguez is represented by the Foster White Gallery and his work can be found at two sites on the UW campus. A version of his 12-piece series based on the Chinese zodiac hangs in the Bill & Melinda Gates Center for Computer Science and Engineering. Rodriguez features the 12 animals::: but his version uses creatures of Central and South America in place of the Chinese animals traditionally featured.

#UWdiscovers

MAGAZINE.WASHINGTON.EDU
George Rodriguez::: '09::: tells stories of identity and humanity through his art

Learning about India just became a little easier for students. Alumni and longtime donors S. Rao and Usha Varanasi have made a $100:::000 gift to the Jackson School of International Studies at University of Washington.

The new fund‚Äîthe S. Rao and Usha Varanasi Endowed Scholarship for Studies of India in the Jackson School‚Äîwill allow greater opportunity for the study of India by students in any discipline::: with a focus on support for undergraduates. The reason for the gift? ‚ÄúOur endowment is an encouragement to students to learn about India from renowned teachers and experts because knowledge deepens empathy:::‚Äù said the Varanasis.

Over 2:::000 undergraduates take courses taught by South Asia Center UW program faculty::: including courses on India‚Äôs contemporary politics::: culture::: development::: public health::: history::: religion::: environment::: social movements::: as well as courses in Hindi::: Urdu::: Bangla and Sanskrit.

This #TBT we return to some essential moments in Seattle‚Äôs LGBTQIA+ history. In 1933::: same-sex bars like The Double Header::: began to open to combat Washington‚Äôs sodomy laws. The Double Header is said to be the longest-operating gay bar in the nation until it closed in 2015. Gay bars in the 1930s were prominent in the Pioneer Square area and helped working-class men and women look for partners.

Drag performances became a crucial feature of the LGBTQIA+ community. Among them is drag artist Francis Renault (pictured here in the second photo)::: known for embodying actress Lillian Russell.

The first Gay Pride March::: captured here in the third photo::: was in 1977. What started as Gay Pride week initiated the annual celebration of LGBTQIA+ Pride and began Capitol Hill‚Äôs reputation as the center for increasing visibility of sexual minorities. In the 1990s::: many LGBTQIA+ organizations emerged to address minorities of distinct racial and cultural backgrounds::: such as Emerald City Black Pride::: Pride Asia::: Entre Hermanos::: Trikone Northwest::: Noor and many more.

Seattle‚Äôs LGBTQIA+ history has been about laws::: morality::: understanding::: cultural and political expressions and city space. It is imperative to recognize Seattle community members who have challenged heterosexist oppression and fought to live a life free of judgment and persecution. #PrideMonth

In a normal year::: students in Griggs‚Äô annual Scan|Design Master Studio course would design and build their own furniture on campus ‚Äî and travel to Copenhagen to study Denmark‚Äôs iconic design style. Courtney Schupp never thought her graduate research at the University of Washington School of Public Health would involve digging through trash. Yet in 2017::: she found herself meticulously sorting each bit of garbage::: recycling and food waste from City of Auburn public school lunchrooms. She was especially interested in still-edible food that could be ‚Äúrescued‚Äù and used to feed hungry people.

Schupp‚Äôs project::: carried out with a team of nine undergraduates::: was one of 16 in the UW‚Äôs inaugural UW Livable City Year program::: which taps the creativity and expertise of students and faculty across disciplines to address local governments‚Äô sustainability goals.

Across the 15 Auburn schools they studied::: the students found more than 85:::000 calories of edible food in a single day of waste sorting::: which could make a big difference in a city where 16% of people experience food insecurity. The students gave each school an individualized report::: which they used to improve their practices.
#ThisIsUW #PopulationHealth

Seattle‚Äôs Japanese community received little to no support during this time minus those in leadership positions like the University of Washington‚Äôs President Lee Seig::: who facilitated transfers of Japanese students to avoid being incarcerated. Pictured here is a representation of the continued resilience and welcoming new life for generations to come. #TBT #AAPIHM

Just a few days shy of the first day of spring::: scientists at Friday Harbor Laboratories on San Juan Island had reason to celebrate. Dozens of juvenile sea stars::: no bigger than a poppy seed::: had successfully metamorphosed from floating larvae to mini star ‚Äî the important first step toward becoming an adult. These young animals represent the first attempt to raise sunflower sea stars in captivity.

The species::: once abundant from Alaska to Southern California::: was nearly destroyed by a mysterious wasting disease that has affected many sea stars in the ocean::: but none so catastrophic as the sunflower star. In December::: the species was listed as critically endangered by the International Union for Conservation of Nature::: prompting a new focus on recovery efforts ‚Äî including captive breeding.

Counterclockwise from the top: Sunflower sea star larvae::: about a month old::: seen under a microscope; one-year-old juvenile sea stars; adult sea stars.

Read more via University of Washington News: https://www.washington.edu/news/2021/04/27/thousands-of-baby-sea-stars-born-at-uw-lab-are-sign-of-hope-for-endangered-species/

column3:
Hi Joshua. Maybe I can help. I was a student reporter for the UW Daily in 1975 when large numbers of Vietnamese boat people were housed two places in the US: Camp Pendleton::: and Camp Murray near Ft. Lewis. I went down there to see the camp. It was a huge story at the time.
These refugees had just been plucked out of the water or had gotten out on the last flights out of Saigon. There were hundreds of them::: families::: former South Vietnamese soldiers::: speaking no English and having nothing except the clothes on their back. They came here because many of them would have been executed by the NVA for helping the US war effort. It is quite possible that I saw this kid's parents there at Camp Murray. It is amazing to me the way these refugees came here with nothing and how they built a community::: asking for no help or assistance::: and integrated themselves into American life. Their very existence was threatened because they worked for us or helped the US war effort::: yet they asked for nothing but a place to live. It's not American exceptionalism that is the story here::: but Vietnamese exceptionalism.
They take away nothing from us or earlier immigrants::: but they have contributed greatly to our society. After 45 years and my trip to Camp Murray::: I still am amazed at the Vietnamese community. I think they have done more for us than we ever did for them. And the kid's story isn't virtue signaling::: it's what we used to call a human interest story. As a UW journalism grad::: I wish him the best in his writing career.

I announced on my class's Discord Server (set up by a student::: of course) the new requirement::: and my students‚Äîmost of whom vaccinated by now::: others making their appointments‚Äîar
e ECSTATIC.

I'd really like people commenting from out of state::: people not at the UW::: ignorant of the fact that vaccines have long been required both in K-12 and on college campuses::: ignorant of the fact that the UW has medical and religious and philosophical exemptions::: to take a moment. Breathe with me. I write this as a UW professor who has been teaching remotely since last March. I am very close w/ my students::: I have done loads to create community and real friendship among them (and us: from movie nights I host on Zoom to being on class Discord servers to arranging virtual field trips). It has been about three times as time consuming than on-campus teaching::: and I am happy to have done it. My students are awesome.

I have been teaching a lot of freshmen this year. Freshmen who have never been to campus or in a college classroom. Freshmen who ended high school remotely. Freshmen who have "known" each other since Fall::: who have never met in person.

Our students want to be on campus::: and the want to be on campus safely. They want their faculty to be healthy::: so we can teach classes. They want their fellow students to be vaccinated::: so they can feel comfortable hanging out with them::: as students should be.

I talk with my students a lot about the pandemic and vaccine when the hop into Zoom office hours::: or stay after class to chat as I sit teaching in my basement. We chat on Discord about it.

There is no talk of "this isn't a vaccine" or "what about my body my choice::: huh?" or "what about my rights this is FASCISM:::" or frankly any of the stuff I am reading in this thread.

They say::: in fact::: "can the UW require this? Will they? I hope so" and "do you think we'll be in person in the Fall?" and "I want to see everyone in person."

They talk about when they get the vaccine::: they share excitement and happiness when they get theirs. When I told them I had gotten my second::: they all‚Äîremotely‚Äîch
eered.

So... listen. This isn't about your politics::: folks. It's about the health of our students::: faculty::: and staff. And I really think it would be wise‚Äîor::: at least::: decent‚Äîto let those of us who care most about our students (including our students) be responsible for this decision.

Thanks for the statement about the recent issue. I am proud to be an alumnus of UW. But racism has been happening in UW for years. I was a graduate student in Mechanical Engineering. The department has not been treating graduate students fairly. The department favors some students for pre-doctoral instructorships
. One student has been assigned for seven and nine quarters. But other students with the same qualification are discouraged. Whenever we ask questions::: they ask us back if we have made any contribution. Otherwise::: we need to shut up. Also::: all internal departmental scholarships are confidential. The selection processes::: the selection criteria::: the awardees::: and the ceremony for celebration are never shared.
In 2016::: when my advisor::: who was in charge of the graduate student seminar::: commented on several graduate students who disturbed the invited speaker by speaking loudly and walking around::: these students form a group called MEGA. They proclaimed that they represent ALL graduate students. The chair was gone. This group of students assumed they were acting chairs. They sent a department-wise
email to slander my advisor. The speaker::: my advisor::: and myself are Chinese.
After I have reported to several units that the department assigned a few graduate students to be the TA of the same courses they had failed in previous quarters::: my advisor received an email in May 2017. I was forced to keep silent and delete all FB posts. "If you say a word about this issue::: you will be in trouble."
column7:
Daddy Changed The World

The six-year old daughter
Of the murdered martyr::: Ray Floyd:::
Abandoned to only his memory:::
Sits high upon a friend‚Äôs shoulders
Unaware of death‚Äôs true finality:::
And shouts an unexpected anthem::: ‚ÄúDaddy changed the world.‚Äù

In a nation of brutality and scourge
Of endemic racism and bias
Against the downtrodden minority:::
Comes the voice of regeneration:::
Comes the sense of the future:::
Comes the reason for the protests:::
A young black child in innocence.
She::: so full of wide-eyed hope
Despite the loss of her protector:::
Says directly into the microphone:::
‚ÄúDaddy changed the world.‚Äù

In the mass of now-joined humanity
There is a whiff of human evolution:::
In the cloud of tear-gas repression:::
A time of a momentous change
In amongst the gathered multitude.
We must hear the clarion of change
As if were come down from the mountain:::
As if we had all marched across that bridge:::
As if Martin Luther King was still alive:::
As it comes out of a babe‚Äôs mouth:::
‚ÄúDaddy changed the world.‚Äù

James N.

Still struggling to get adjusted to a new sleep schedule after daylight savings time kicked in? University of Washington School of Law professor Steve Calandrillo breaks down the benefits of staying on daylight time all year round::: as well as the history of springing forward and falling back.

University of Washington School of Law posted a video to playlist Three-Minute Legal Tips.
12 March::: 12:13 ¬∑

Each spring::: every state but two "springs forward" from the dark winter into the brighter days of daylight saving time.

The switch has been in place since World War I::: when European countries figured out they could save oil and energy by delaying the sunset. So::: if daylight saving time is so beneficial::: why doesn't everywhere have it year round?

For years::: UW Law Professor Steve Calandrillo has been begging this very question. In three minutes::: he shares insights into the practice's history and discusses the potentially major benefits a permanent switch could bring.

The Department of American Indian Studies at the University of Washington instructor and Squaxin artist Joe Seymour has made Salish salmon a permanent art fixture to the Olympia waterfront. His work adorns a new apartment complex on Fifth Avenue and even lights up at night.

"The salmon for the Views on Fifth tower are meant to be swimming up stream to spawn. The top three salmon have already begun their journey up river::: while the bottom salmon is waiting in a shallow pool at the bottom of the falls:::" says Seymour. "The building sits on the mouth of the Deschutes River and empties into Budd Inlet::: traditionally known to the Squaxin Island people as Steh-Chass (place of the black bear). Before Olympia was settled::: that area used to be an estuary with a very diverse ecosystem. There is a movement around Olympia gathering momentum to return that area back to an estuary and remove the fish dam on the Fifth Ave bridge. This installation honors the promise that the ancestors of the Squaxin Island tribe made to the salmon people that humans would always treat the salmon people and their home with respect and reverence. It‚Äôs my wish that with the salmon on that building::: we will always remember our promise to be stewards of the land and to ensure that the salmon will always have a home to return to."

AIS.WASHINGTON.EDU
AIS Instructor Joe Seymour Brings Coast Salish Salmon to Olympia Waterfront | American Indian Studies | University of Washington

Former UW student Ron Chew uses his personal history as scaffolding for the story of Seattle ‚Äî from early Chinese immigration over a century ago to Black Lives Matter protests this past summer.

While working for The Daily::: Chew stood up to racism at a young age after he applied to be news editor. As an experienced staff member who had helped with editing and training new reporters::: he thought he was an excellent candidate. But the editor-in-chief offered the post to other students ‚Äî white ‚Äî who hadn‚Äôt applied for the job. ‚ÄúI thought I deserved at least the courtesy of an interview:::‚Äù Chew says.

Fueled by frustration and with a view to other examples of discrimination at the paper::: Chew filed a complaint with the UW human rights office. He noted that people of color at The Daily rarely advanced beyond the position of reporter. Six months later::: an investigator from the office issued a report validating Chew‚Äôs grievance and noting that the student newspaper didn‚Äôt have clear hiring guidelines::: job descriptions or minimum qualifications. She recommended the newspaper provide back pay to Chew and that the board that advised The Daily be diversified.

MAGAZINE.WASHINGTON.EDU
Ron Chew‚Äôs memoir captures the soul of Seattle‚Äôs International District

"When I completed my undergraduate work at Dartmouth College::: women made up only 35% of the program I was in:::" April Stempien-Otero::: MD::: FACC::: says. "There were only five women in my residency class. At some point along the way::: I was told that women couldn‚Äôt become interventional cardiologists."

"Today::: there continues to be a perception that cardiology is a male-dominated field. I forget this at the University of Washington because we have so many women faculty:::" Stempien-Otero says. "When I go to a large national meeting::: however::: I look around and I see it. I am writing to ask that you modernize and humanize medical training at the University of Washington (UW) by ending the use of live animals in the general surgery residency program. UW's surgery residents are now instructed to cut into live pigs to practice procedures. This follows a five-year span where modern::: human-relevant training methods were used instead of animals. However::: as you know::: there are validated and widely available methods that allow trainees to repeat procedures and hone their skills‚Äîwithout harming animals.

Currently::: 76 percent of surveyed programs (198 of 259) in the United States use only human-relevant training methods. In addition::: UW‚Äôs state-of-the-ar
t facility‚Äîthe WWAMI Institute for Simulation in Healthcare‚Äîoffe
rs a full range of nonanimal training methods including purpose-designe
d simulators::: which were used to train surgery residents during the five year lapse in animal use.

To ensure that future surgeons are receiving educationally and ethically superior training methods::: please end the use of animals immediately.

UW School of Social Work
1 February::: 09:19 ¬∑

February is Black History Month and we are celebrating social worker and civil rights trailblazer Whitney M. Young Jr.::: born a century ago in Lincoln Ridge::: Ky.::: on July 31::: 1921. After serving in World War II::: Young switched his career interest from medicine to social work. He earned a BS in social work from Kentucky State University and an MSW from the University of Minnesota. After teaching for several years::: in 1954 he was appointed the first dean of social work at Atlanta University in Georgia.

Young championed civil rights and equal opportunity as head of the National Urban League::: a position he held from 1961 until his death in 1971. He launched a 10-point "domestic Marshall Plan:::" a strategy to combat poverty and close the wealth gap between Blacks and whites::: an initiative that strongly influenced the federal poverty programs of the 1960s. Young was an advisor to Presidents John F. Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson on civil rights issues::: and received the nation‚Äôs highest civilian award::: the Presidential Medal of Freedom::: from President Johnson in 1969.

Find out about UW Black History Month events here: http://bit.ly/3pM5O0M #BlackHistoryMonth2021

artist Wangechi Mutu. It will move to its new home at the UW in front of the plaza of the Hans Rosling Center for Population Health this winter.

Known for her powerful and distinctive use of the female form to explore gender::: identity::: cultural trauma and environmental degradation::: Mutu created four 7-foot bronze statues to occupy the empty niches of the fa√ßade of the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York for an exhibit. She references the caryatid‚Äîa sculpture where a woman‚Äôs body is used as structural or architectural support‚Äîa theme in many African traditions of classical status objects::: like royal stools and staffs::: as well as in Greek architecture. ‚ÄúI love the idea of a classical figure that one adores and is drawn to and one has no idea why:::‚Äù she says.

Mutu blended these different traditions and redefined the concept of the caryatid to be an independent and powerful woman who can ‚Äúlead us into the future. Take us to where we haven‚Äôt been before.‚Äù The circular plates are reminiscent of futuristic crowns or halos::: or magical orbs that emphasize composure and wisdom. They are inspired by traditional lip adornments worn by women of status from certain African traditions

The 900-pound bronze statue was fabricated at the Walla Walla Foundry in southeastern Washington and brought to the UW through a gift of the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation."

I hope that in the playlist there was no cry of horror and slaughter from the caged monkeys. It would be unnecessary to know the horrors that monkeys go through (strangulation:::
dehydration::: hunger::: among others). In the wild nature these situations would not occur. Just one look ... Stuck in small cages::: without the possibility of exploring large spaces as is typical of monkeys::: lonely and afraid::: subject to situations they don't deserve. To expose the situation in this way could be called sentimentality:::
but it is not. It is empathy::: the ability to imagine how the other suffers and their pain::: their deprivation and what it does::: whoever it is::: animal or human. It is a sophistication in the humanization process::: in the quality of thoughts and feelings (since one leads to the other).
What I mean are lives::: whose right to freedom has been taken away::: lives that have been subjected to degradation::: subjected to barbaric experiments::: that look more like torture::: the result of which is innocuous and of no use. And::: after being exhausted::: having their lives debased and sucked::: they are killed and discarded::: as if they were worthless::: as if they had no feelings::: as if they came out of nowhere. What I am reporting is practiced by scientists! What kind of science is this in the 21st century. Where is humanism?
It's shameful! What a horrible way to deal with Life! What a terrible sleep to assert itself as a "superior primate"::: rational::: to explore and take the life of another in an admittedly old-fashioned and inefficient experiment. How many more lives will be taken::: without any ethical and moral limits::: hidden under the fallacious euphemism "scientific interest"?

From prisons to neuroscience labs::: Paul Tubig finds philosophy everywhere.

A current UW doctoral candidate in the UW Department of Philosophy::: Tubig was recently awarded the Graduate School Medal::: an annual honor recognizing doctoral students for their academic expertise and social commitment to their community. He taught philosophy at the Washington Corrections Center for Women in Gig Harbor and worked with the Center for Neurotechnology to develop an ethics dialogue tool for neuroscientists at the UW. Tubig is also an affiliate member of the Disability Studies Program at the University of Washington.

‚ÄúFor many of these women who are now in prison::: they have to deal with all of these stigmas::: which in a lot of ways shape how they see themselves:::‚Äù Tubig says. ‚ÄúStudying philosophy helps in thinking ... it‚Äôs ok to question how other people have been describing you or labeling you or seeing you.‚Äù #ThisisUW #HuskyExperience

Scientists now know why more than half of the coho salmon that return to Puget Sound's urban streams die before they can spawn: A chemical that keeps tires from breaking down too quickly.

‚ÄúMost people think that we know what chemicals are toxic and all we have to do is control the amount of those chemicals to make sure water quality is fine. But::: in fact::: animals are exposed to this giant chemical soup and we don‚Äôt know what many of the chemicals in it even are:::‚Äù said co-senior author Edward Kolodziej::: an associate professor in both the UW Tacoma Division of Sciences & Mathematics and the UW Department of Civil & Environmental Engineering.

‚ÄúHere we started with a mix of 2:::000 chemicals and were able to get all the way down to this one highly toxic chemical::: something that kills large fish quickly and we think is probably found on every single busy road in the world.‚Äù

WASHINGTON.EDU
Tire-related chemical is largely responsible for adult coho salmon deaths in urban streams

It's #PersonalSpaceDay ‚Äî how about getting some personal space by living on our moon!? UW researchers are part of a group of organizations working on bringing wireless charging to the moon::: which would allow humans and robots to live and work there. üåñ

Moon dust presents a big challenge::: however::: as particles can interfere with charging stations.

‚ÄúMoon dust is very fine and tends to stick to surfaces because it gets electrically charged. The UW team is tackling the fundamental research question of how dust particle size and composition affects power transfer efficiency:::‚Äù said UW lead researcher Joshua Smith::: a professor in both the Paul G. Allen School of Computer Science & Engineering and the Department of Electrical & Computer Engineering. ‚ÄúWe plan to take an approach that is a hybrid of science and engineering: We will develop a synthetic moon dust that is consistent with known relevant properties::: but that represents the worst case for our wireless power transfer system.

WASHINGTON.EDU
UW part of $5.8M contract to study wireless charging on moon

column7: Was surprised to see the game on the government ship I work on here in Hawaii on American Forces Television. Enjoyed the game::: great win::: but I thought Coach Lake was a defensive specialist. If so::: has he been in discussions with Coach Norton over on the Seahawks?::: Why you ask? While the offense did a great job moving the ball up and down the field::: apparently::: ORST had no issue moving the ball either. 4 man front did little to stop the running game by ORST::: and I only noted 3 times that delayed blitz's were run. A great example of a missed opportunity was in the second half when the punter and special teams pinned the Beavers on the 1 yard line::: the perfect opportunity to bring the house. Instead::: the same old 4-3 defense that struggled to stop the run game all game::: and lo and behold::: ORST was able to run itself out of trouble. Washington's defense in the past has been fantastic in stopping the run (actually::: one of the tops in the nation for the past 5 years)::: but last night was not very good. I chalk it up to first game on the field::: and fingers crossed it gets better. If so::: Huskies finish 5-0 and move on to the PAC-12 championship! Go Dawgs.

column1: When Helen Louise Noyes graduated from the UW in 1969::: she interviewed for numerous corporate management training programs. Most were resistant to hiring a woman. Noyes went on to a long career with the CIA before retiring in 2006. Inspired by her work experience and her love of languages::: she recently created the Jonathan and Helen Louise Noyes Language Scholarship Fund in the Jackson School of International Studies. column1: The 19th amendment turns 100 years old today::: marking a milestone victory for Women's Suffrage. In doing so::: however::: many white suffragists were willing to sacrifice progress for Black women. And in the century since::: our national myth-making has continued to erase and discount the importance of women of color to the suffrage movement. column1: Before Darius Presley (BA::: Communication::: 2020) decided to major in Communication::: he wondered if the University of Washington was the place for him. But after declaring::: his professor::: Kathleen Fearn-Banks::: encouraged him to apply for the Flip Wilson Scholarship. ‚ÄúTo have her notice me that way made me realize I did belong. It came out of nowhere at the most opportune time:::‚Äù says Presley. The scholarship::: funded by the estate of American comedian and actor Flip Wilson::: helps outstanding students who seek a career in communications. As part of his studies and with support from the scholarship::: Presley took a class with Professor Ralina Joseph that focused on a collaborative community project with the Northwest African American Museum based on her UW ‚ÄúInterrupting Privilege‚Äù course. This class facilitated intergenerational conversation on challenging topics around race. Presley says: ‚ÄúBefore [the course]::: I‚Äôd thought about race::: but I hadn‚Äôt thought about all the intersectionalities of being Black -\-\ how people experience it differently due to gender::: education::: and other things... It opened my eyes to how much I thought I knew but did not.‚Äù ‚ÄúI‚Äôd like to continue to be part of the conversation:::‚Äù Presley says. ‚ÄúThere‚Äôs so much more for me still to learn.‚Äù https://bit.ly/2F3GKzX #PhilanthropyFriday  ARTSCI.WASHINGTON.EDU Support to Study Race & Privilege

column1: Some good (and bad) news for sharks! ü¶à  While coastal shark populations are on the decline (the bad news)::: researchers are finding they're doing well in others places with good management::: indicating that there may be more hope for these fishes than was previously thought.  ‚ÄúAt twenty percent of the reefs we surveyed::: we didn‚Äôt detect any sharks where you would expect to see them:::‚Äù says Aaron Wirsing::: associate professor in the UW College of the Environment and collaborator on the project. ‚ÄúThat was alarming and a bit of a surprise. But in other places::: even those with lots of human activity and tourism::: like the Bahamas::: sharks are doing relatively well.
